<p>Rumors abound that Apple is about to redesign all its operating systems, dramatically changing the devices we use every day starting this fall. It would be a perfectly understandable reaction to wonder why Apple would focus on aesthetics while so many parts of its business seem to be in turmoil.</p>
<p>But I’m here to propose the opposite. That a lot of the symptoms of what Apple’s done wrong lately — most powerfully represented by the disastrous update to the macOS Settings (formerly System Preferences) app — are actually reasons why now it’s past time for Apple to turn the page, design something new, and announce it at WWDC in June.</p>
